<bibRefCitation author="Goodwin, G. G. &amp; A. M. Greenhall" journalOrPublisher="Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist." pageId="119" pageNumber="119" pagination="191 - 301" part="122" refId="ref94360" refString="Goodwin, G. G., and A. M. Greenhall 1961. A review of the bats of Trinidad and Tobago: descriptions, rabies infection, and ecology. Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist. 122: 191 - 301." title="A review of the bats of Trinidad and Tobago: descriptions, rabies infection, and ecology" type="journal article" year="1961">Goodwin and Greenhall (1961)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Husson, A. M." bookContentInfo="282 pp." box="[373,556,1476,1499]" journalOrPublisher="Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52" pageId="119" pageNumber="119" refId="ref95767" refString="Husson, A. M. 1962. The bats of Suriname. Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52: 282 pp. 1 30 pls." title="The bats of Suriname" type="book" year="1962">Husson (1962</bibRefCitation>
, 1978), 
<bibRefCitation author="Gardner, A. L. &amp; D. C. Carter" box="[128,447,1505,1528]" journalOrPublisher="J. Mammal." pageId="119" pageNumber="119" pagination="72 - 82" part="53" refId="ref93424" refString="Gardner, A. L., and D. C. Carter 1972. A review of the Peruvian species of Vampyrops (Chiroptera: Phyllosomatidae). J. Mammal. 53: 72 - 82." title="A review of the Peruvian species of Vampyrops (Chiroptera: Phyllosomatidae)" type="journal article" year="1972">Gardner and Carter (1972)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Rouk, C. S. &amp; D. C. Carter" bookContentInfo="7 pp." journalOrPublisher="Occas. Pap. Mus. Texas Tech Univ" pageId="119" pageNumber="119" refId="ref99776" refString="Rouk, C. S., and D. C. Carter 1972. A new species of Vampyrops (Chiroptera: Phyllostomatidae) from South America. Occas. Pap. Mus. Texas Tech Univ. 1: 7 pp." title="A new species of Vampyrops (Chiroptera: Phyllostomatidae) from South America" type="book" year="1972">Rouk and Carter (1972)</bibRefCitation>
, Swanepoel and 
<bibRefCitation author="Genoways, H. H. &amp; S. L. Williams" box="[432,652,1534,1557]" journalOrPublisher="Ann. Carnegie Mus." pageId="119" pageNumber="119" pagination="323 - 335" part="48" refId="ref93773" refString="Genoways, H. H., and S. L. Williams 1979. Records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname. Ann. Carnegie Mus. 48: 323 - 335." title="Records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname" type="journal article" year="1979">Genoways (1979)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Brosset, A. &amp; P. Charles-Dominique" box="[128,599,1564,1587]" journalOrPublisher="Mammalia" pageId="119" pageNumber="119" pagination="509 - 559" part="54" refId="ref91807" refString="Brosset, A., and P. Charles-Dominique 1990. The bats from French Guiana: a taxonomic, faunistic and ecological approach. Mammalia 54: 509 - 559." title="The bats from French Guiana: a taxonomic, faunistic and ecological approach" type="journal article" year="1990">Brosset and Charles­Dominique (1990)</bibRefCitation>
, and Anderson (1997). Two subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1866" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Platyrrhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="119" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helleri">
<emphasis box="[576,594,1593,1616]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">helleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are currently recognized, of which 
<emphasis box="[599,617,1623,1646]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[634,649,1623,1646]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">h</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[128,225,1652,1675]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">incarum</emphasis>
ranges throughout Amazonia, including the Guianas (Koopman, 1994).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="119.[128,657,1036,1763]" lastBlockId="119.[704,1233,845,1425]" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">
Our Paracou specimens conform closely with previous descriptions of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1866" box="[510,780,845,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Platyrrhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="119" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helleri">
<emphasis box="[510,780,845,1763]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">Platyrrhinus helleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Although some populations (e.g., in Bolivia; 
<bibRefCitation author="Anderson, S." box="[806,994,874,897]" editor="H. H. Genoways &amp; R. J. Baker" journalOrPublisher="Lubbock, TX: Mus. Texas Tech Univ" pageId="119" pageNumber="119" pagination="89 - 93" refId="ref90916" refString="Anderson, S. 1996. Notes on Bolivian mammals, 8. Small species of Platyrrhinus. In H. H. Genoways and R. J. Baker (eds.), Contributions in mammalogy: a memorial volume honoring Dr. J. Knox Jones, Jr.: 89 - 93. Lubbock, TX: Mus. Texas Tech Univ." title="Notes on Bolivian mammals, 8. Small species of Platyrrhinus" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Contributions in mammalogy: a memorial volume honoring Dr. J. Knox Jones, Jr" year="1996">Anderson, 1996</bibRefCitation>
) exhibit variation in the number of accessory cusps present on the anterior margin of the second lower premolar, all of our vouchers have only a single accessory cusp in this location. Measurements of the Paracou series (table 44) fall within the range of variation previously reported for 
<emphasis box="[832,850,1080,1103]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[867,882,1080,1103]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">h</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[899,996,1080,1103]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">incarum</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="119" pageNumber="119" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="119.[704,1233,845,1425]" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">
FIELD OBSERVATIONS: We captured 14 individuals of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1866" box="[856,1090,1139,1162]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Platyrrhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="119" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helleri">
<emphasis box="[856,1090,1139,1162]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="119">Platyrrhinus helleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at Paracou, of which 11 were taken in ground­level mistnets and 3 in elevated mistnets. Four groundlevel captures were in well­drained primary forest, one in swampy primary forest, two in creekside primary forest, two in manmade clearings, and two over roadside puddles. The three elevated net captures were made between 6 and 21 m above a narrow dirt road.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
